💻 Sample SQL Queries
1. Total Points Earned by Each Customer
SELECT 
    customer_id,
    SUM(points_earned) AS total_points
FROM flights
GROUP BY customer_id
ORDER BY total_points DESC;
2. Most Active Customers (by flights taken)
SELECT 
    customer_id,
    COUNT(flight_id) AS total_flights
FROM flights
GROUP BY customer_id
ORDER BY total_flights DESC;
3. Average Distance Traveled per Customer
SELECT 
    customer_id,
    AVG(distance) AS avg_distance
FROM flights
GROUP BY customer_id;
4. Loyalty Tier Performance
SELECT 
    c.loyalty_tier,
    COUNT(f.flight_id) AS total_flights,
    SUM(f.points_earned) AS total_points
FROM customers c
JOIN flights f
ON c.customer_id = f.customer_id
GROUP BY c.loyalty_tier
ORDER BY total_points DESC;
📊 Key Insights (Example Section)
High-tier loyalty members contribute the most points but are fewer in number
A small group of customers accounts for most flight activity
Points redemption is significantly lower than points earned
Customer activity is uneven across loyalty tiers

📌 Conclusion

This analysis provides insights into customer engagement within the airline loyalty program. The findings can help the airline improve reward structures, increase customer retention, and design better loyalty incentives.
